The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | QUICK TAKES
                                                                                                                       7                                      QUICK TAKES
                      
	When Becks met Tutu                 
	Cape Town: David Beckham has shared a philosophical moment with retired Cape Town Archbishop Desmond Tutu. According to a statement issued by the Desmond Tutu Peace Center, the two chatted over tea Thursday at Tutus office.         
	Beckham was quoted as telling Tutu that he was disappointed not to be playing in this years World Cup.         
	No worry         
	Nelspruit: Chilean team officials stepped in on Friday to knock down fears  sparked by his wife  that playmaker Jorge Valdivia would miss their next World Cup match against Switzerland with a thigh injury. A team spokesman said Valdivias injury was minor and Chile midfielder Rodrigo Millar said he was confident his teammate would recover in time to play in Mondays Group H game in Port Elizabeth.         
	Job hunting         
	Johannesburg: Former World Cup winner Osvaldo Ardiles wants to be Australia coach. Dutchman Pim Verbeek will step down from the position at the end of the World Cup and Ardiles, who won the trophy with Argentina in 1978, is interested in the job.         
	Fifa check         
	Johannesburg: Fifa is preparing to monitor the World Cups most vulnerable matches for match-fixing threats. Fifa legal director Marco Villiger says the final group-stage games are at the highest risk of being fixed, especially those that involve teams which have already qualified for the second round or have been knocked out.         
	MLS plans         
	Johannesburg: North Americas Major League Soccer plans to bring in several faces from the World Cup in a bid to exploit the boom in interest in the event, the leagues head of recruitment said. MLS recently changed the Beckham rule to allow clubs to sign up to three players who, like LA Galaxys David Beckham, are not part of the salary cap system.         
	Jail ticket         
	Pretoria: A Nigerian man has been sentenced to three years in prison by a World Cup court in South Africa for being in unlawful possession of 30 match tickets. Police said Kunle Benjamin was sentenced on Wednesday after he could not give a satisfactory explanation why he had the tickets in his possession.           AGENCIES                                                                                                                 
